{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17640382","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17640382"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:15:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:15:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17825"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17825","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17825"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.27,0.09,0.09,0.27,0.27]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10539"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73257"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10539","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10539"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17825"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58728"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5714"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24583"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25019"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73257","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73257"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman with metastatic ovarian cancer is experiencing severe, unrelenting pain despite regular opioid analgesia. Her palliative care physician increases her morphine dose to better control her symptoms, while acknowledging this may potentially depress her respiratory rate.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the ethical principle that supports this decision?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["The doctrine of double effect","The principle of proportionality","The principle of therapeutic privilege","Beneficence outweighs all other principles","Utilitarian risk-benefit analysis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe doctrine of double effect\u003C/strong\u003E states that an action which may cause harm can be ethically justified if:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe action itself is morally good or neutral\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe harmful effect is not intended but may be foreseen\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe good effect outweighs the potential harm\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe good effect is not achieved through the harmful effect\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe principle of proportionality\u003C/strong\u003E considers only the balance between benefits and harms, but does not address the crucial element of intention that is central to double effect.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe principle of therapeutic privilege\u003C/strong\u003E relates to withholding information from patients when disclosure would cause harm, which is not relevant to this scenario.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBeneficence outweighs all other principles\u003C/strong\u003E represents an oversimplified approach that fails to consider the nuanced ethical framework needed in complex clinical decisions.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUtilitarian risk-benefit analysis\u003C/strong\u003E focuses solely on outcomes and consequences, whereas double effect specifically considers the importance of intention alongside outcomes.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, the intention is to relieve suffering (good effect), while potentially hastening death (harmful effect) is foreseen but not intended. The relief of severe suffering is considered proportionate to the risk.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The doctrine of double effect states that an action which causes harm may be ethically permissible if the harm was not intended and the good effect outweighs the harm.","In palliative care, providing adequate pain relief is ethically justified even if it may unintentionally hasten death.","The four conditions of double effect are: good intention, proportionate reason, no direct harm intended, and good effect not achieved through bad means."],"references":["Mandal J, Ponnambath DK, Parija SC. Bioethics: A brief review. Trop Parasitol. 2017;7(1):5-7. doi:10.4103/tp.TP_4_17","Varkey B. Principles of Clinical Ethics and Their Application to Practice. Med Princ Pract. 2021;30(1):17-28. doi:10.1159/000509119"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58728"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17825"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58728","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58728"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-23T09:53:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-09T00:31:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10539"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73257"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null